The standard approach in .NET is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:

```csharp
public interface IFileSystem
{
    string ReadAllText(string path);
    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);
    bool DirectoryExists(string path);
}
```

Then implement it with the real calls:

```csharp
public class FileSystem : IFileSystem
{
    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);
    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);
    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**In your classes**, inject `IFileSystem` instead of calling `File`/`Directory` directly. **In tests**, pass a mock or fake implementation.

Alternatively, if you're on .NET 7+, you can use the built-in `System.IO.Abstractions`-style approach — Microsoft now ships `IFileSystem` via the **`Microsoft.Extensions.FileSystemGlobbing`** package, or you can use the popular **[System.IO.Abstractions](https://github.com/TestableIO/System.IO.Abstractions)** NuGet package which provides `IFileSystem` out of the box with an in-memory test helper (`MockFileSystem`).

**TL;DR:** Don't call `File.*` / `Directory.*` directly — hide them behind an interface, inject it, and mock it in tests.
